sting is that this calamitous feeling — that the world I had grown up in was being swept away — wasn&#39;t really related to wokeness, or Donald Trump, or social media, or any of the factors that people ( <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/honestly-its-probably-the-phones">including me</a> ) typically associate with the ruptures of the 2010s. But of course I felt those changes too, just a few months later — Gamergate and the Ferguson protests in the summer of 2014, and the rise of Trump a year later.</p><p> Looking back, it&#39;s easy to see that the early to mid 2010s — the period between 2012 and 2015 — was a turning point in both American society and world events. Figuring out why is harder. As far as I can tell, it was a lucky confluence of several events — technological, economic, political, and geopolitical.</p><h4> The geopolitical break</h4><p><a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/why-did-the-world-break-in-the-early">阅读更多</a></p>; 
